mortality rate roughly half that for U.S. males over the entire period. In 
contrast, U.S. white female mortality rates, though roughly equal to those for 
Swedish females in 1950-51, experienced a relatively more rapid increase; their 
rates were double the Swedish rates by 1980. The factors contributing to these 
patterns, such as marked cohort differences in risk, are identified by the 
various stages of analysis.

